  <h1>FUTO Keyboard Review: An Android Keyboard that is Private and Functional</h1>
  <time datetime="2024-07-03">3 July 2024</time>
</header>

<h3>1. Your Android Keyboard is Most Likely Spying on You</h3>

<p>If you are using an Android device it is possible that your keyboard application is highly insecure and spying on you.</p>

<p>If you are using a third party keyboard this risk is highly likely. Personalized text prediction and auto correct are often delivered through your key inputs being uploaded to the keyboard provider's servers. <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/335428/smartphone-keyboards-are-a-privacy-nightmare/#why-keyboards-are-so-dangerous" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">This is a privacy nightmare</a>.</p>

<p>Think about all the things that you have typed into your phone's keyboard: highly intimate messages, sensitive medical records and confidential business information. You do not want this leaving your device.</p>

<p>The keyboard app you use may be malicious. In 2022 Google removed many malicious apps, including keyboards, downloaded a <a href="https://wp.nyu.edu/itsecurity/2022/07/29/android-users-confirm-you-dont-have-malicious-apps-on-your-device/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">staggering 10 million+ times.</a></p>

<p>Even non-malicious keyboard apps cannot be trusted. Some examples:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>"SwiftKey users started reporting that their keyboard was suggesting random foreign words and even unfamiliar email addresses."</em> - <a href="https://www.androidauthority.com/swiftkey-suspends-service-data-leak-706680/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><strong>Android Authority</strong></a></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>"A team of security researchers has discovered a massive trove of personal data belonging to more than 31 million users of the virtual keyboard app AI.type, leaked online for anyone to download."</em> - <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2017/12/keyboard-data-breach.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><strong>The Hacker News</strong></a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>A recent Citizen Lab investigation found that <a href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2024/04/24/1091740/chinese-keyboard-app-security-encryption/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">"almost every Chinese keyboard app has a security flaw that reveals what users type,"</a> leaving nearly 1 billion people vulnerable to eavesdropping.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><em>"we estimate that up to one billion users are affected by these vulnerabilities. Given the scope of these vulnerabilities, the sensitivity of what users type on their devices, the ease with which these vulnerabilities may have been discovered, and that the Five Eyes have previously exploited similar vulnerabilities in Chinese apps for surveillance, it is possible that such users' keystrokes may have also been under mass surveillance."</em> - <a href="https://citizenlab.ca/2024/04/vulnerabilities-across-keyboard-apps-reveal-keystrokes-to-network-eavesdroppers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><strong>Citizen Lab</strong></a></p>
</blockquote>

<p>All of this raises the question: why does your keyboard need an internet connection? The internet's business model is <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/oct/04/shoshana-zuboff-surveillance-capitalism-assault-human-automomy-digital-privacy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Surveillance Capitalism</a> after all!</p>

<p>This is where <a href="https://keyboard.futo.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FUTO Keyboard</a> comes in!</p>

